    "response_text": "Across the 100-year simulation period, cumulative destocking exhibits an initial rapid accumulation phase followed by highly divergent long-term patterns. During the first 20 years, all simulation replicates show steep increases from 0 to mean values ranging between 50 and 80 animals destocked per household. This initial phase demonstrates diminishing marginal destocking rates as households adjust from initial stocking levels of 90 animals.\n\nBeyond year 20, outcomes diverge substantially into distinct trajectory clusters. By year 40, cumulative destocking spans from approximately 58 to 110 animals per household. This divergence continues to widen through the remainder of the simulation period.\n\nIn the lower range of outcomes, destocking arrests between years 30-40, stabilizing at cumulative totals of 58-90 animals for the remaining 60-70 years, with negligible additional destocking occurring after year 40. In the upper range, destocking continues at sustained rates of approximately 1-2 animals annually throughout the entire century, reaching final values between 130-173 animals by year 100. Intermediate outcomes occupy the 90-130 range, showing moderate sustained accumulation of 0.5-1.5 animals annually after year 40.\n\nThe final distribution at year 100 spans approximately 115 animals, representing a threefold difference between the lowest (~58) and highest (~173) cumulative destocking outcomes, with the majority of replicates falling in the 80-130 range.\n\n**Implications for Decision Makers:**\n\nThe universal early destocking of 50-80 animals within 20 years indicates that initial stocking levels substantially exceed sustainable carrying capacity under high rainfall variability (coefficient of variation = 0.5), forcing immediate and significant herd reductions across all learning strategies.\n\nThe subsequent bifurcation into arrested versus sustained destocking patterns suggests that stochastic rainfall realizations interact with learning approaches to produce path-dependent outcomes. The lower destocking totals (58-90) represent scenarios where households successfully establish equilibrium stocking rates and stable production systems. Conversely, the upper range (130-173) indicates chronic overstocking or boom-bust cycles involving repeated acquisition and liquidation of animals, implying substantial economic losses and livelihood instability.\n\nThe wide outcome range (58-173) after 100 years demonstrates that under high climatic uncertainty, private pasture management produces highly variable long-term outcomes even with identical initial conditions and behavioral algorithms. The persistence of divergence through year 100 suggests that transient dynamics dominate or that single-loop learning mechanisms fail to converge on uniform sustainable practices. Policymakers should anticipate significant heterogeneity in household outcomes and consider interventions that reduce the incidence of high-destocking trajectories exceeding 120 animals, which represent repeated productive asset liquidation.",
    "code_input": null,
    "image_path": null
}

